The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
 Wednesday, March 17, 2004  The City Diary
																																																		Tension erupted in Jorasanko on Tuesday afternoon when CPM and Trinamul Congress activists picked a fight over wall-writing in Munsi Sagiuddin Lane. 																																																								ne person was admitted to Calcutta Medical College and Hospital with severe injuries, while a Trinamul leader was arrested in connection with the incident. Timir Bhattacharya, officer-in-charge of Jorasanko police station, said a group of Trinamul workers, led by local leader Sanjay Sonkar, wanted to use the southern boundary wall of Rajendralal Mullicks house for election graffiti.																																																								Mohammad Sohrab, an eatery-owner and CPM supporter, who had repaired and whitewashed the wall leading to his hotel, stopped them from doing so. Soon, a scuffle broke out between Sohrab and the Trinamul workers. But we rushed in at the right time, Bhattacharya said. 																																																								oon after the police team left, a mob flaunting CPM flags allegedly assaulted Trinamul youth wing general secretary Swapan Burman, who had arrived on the spot to mediate in the squabble. The situation took a turn for the worse when Sonkars men returned to the spot and seriously injured Mohammad Imtiaz, a security guard at Sohrabs hotel, with a chopper, police said. Sonkar has been arrested, Bhattacharya added. Imtiaz is said to be in a critical condition.																																																		Two men were killed and a girl was injured in three accidents in Howrah on Tuesday. Bicyclist Biswajit Pramanik, 55, was run over by a truck at Shyampur. He was declared dead at a local hospital. The driver fled, leaving the vehicle behind. In another incident, Brajamohan Bhakta, 46, was hit from behind by a truck in Uluberia at around 11 am. He died on the spot. Manisha Khatun, 10, was knocked down by a truck near Panchla in the morning. She was admitted to Uluberia State General Hospital. 																																																		Saira Begum, a 26-year-old housewife of Uluberia, in Howrah, suffered serious burns early on Monday when the stove she was cooking on exploded. Saira is under treatment at Uluberia State General Hospital and is said to be in a critical condition. Police said they were interrogating her husband, Sheikh Barjahan. Sairas parents have alleged that she used to be tortured by her in-laws for dowry.																																																		Four persons including Prosanto Ghosh, the kingpin of a racket that duped unemployed youths, were arrested on Tuesday at Madhyamgram on charges of fraud. Police said Ghosh and his aides would collect money from unemployed youths, promising them government jobs. On Monday, police rescued Ghosh from some local residents who had led an assault on him. Three other members of the gang were picked up later.																																																		Bhola, an extortionist, and four accomplices were arrested on Tuesday at the Hazra Road-Sarat Bose Road crossing. Three firearms, two choppers and four rounds of ammunition were found on them. Police said Bhola was wanted in several cases of extortion. 																																																		The West Bengal Bar Council has made a representation before Calcutta High Court Chief Justice A.K. Mathur to set up morning courts in hot-zone districts during the summer. The council pleaded that the courts of these areas be allowed a two-month summer vacation if the morning courts were not possible.																																																		Deposition in the case filed by US-based doctor Kunal Saha at the National Consumer Redressal Forum, demanding Rs 77 crore from some city doctors, started on Tuesday. Doctors Abani Roy Chowdhury and Baidyanath Halder were examined during the day. 																																																		Netai Charan Chakraborty Homoeopathic Medical College and Hospital in Howrah received a donation of Rs 10,000 on Tuesday for infrastructural improvement. The cheque was handed over to the college authorities by stage actress Dolly Basu.							TO Lions Club of Calcutta Sanjeevani for organising a free IOL eye operation camp in New Alipore
